            <h1>Shrimad Bhagvat Geeta</h1>
            <p>The sermon given by Lord Krishna to Arjun just before the start of the Mahabharata war is known as
                Shrimad Bhagwat Gita . It is a part of the Bhishma Parva of the Mahabharata . The Gita has 18 chapters
                and 700 verses. The Gita is counted among the Prasthanatrayi , which also includes the Upanishads and
                Brahmasutras . Therefore, according to the Indian tradition, the Gita has the same place as the
                Upanishads and Dharmasutras . The Upanishads have been called cow (cow) and the Gita its milk. This
                means that the spiritual knowledge of the Upanishads is accepted by the Gita in its entirety. Many
                knowledges of the Upanishads are in the Gita. For example, Ashwattha Vidya regarding the nature of the
                world, Avyayapurush Vidya regarding the eternal unborn Brahma, Aksharpurush Vidya regarding Para
                Prakriti or the living beings and Ksharpurush Vidya regarding Apara Prakriti or the physical world.
                Thus, the specific content of both the Brahmavada of the Vedas and the spirituality of the Upanishads is
                contained in the Gita. This is called Brahmavidya in the words of Pushpika. </p>


            <p>During the Mahabharata war, when Arjuna refuses to fight, Shri Krishna preaches him and makes him aware
                of the true knowledge of karma and dharma. These teachings of Shri Krishna have been collected in a book
                called Shrimad Bhagwat Geeta.</p>
            <div class="readmore-p">
                <div class="readmore">
                    <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhagavad_Gita">Read More</a>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <h1 class="hedding">Bhagavad Gita Chapters</h1>
